# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aotea-conservation-park
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The area of the park has seen human interaction for approximately 700 years, with evidence of habitation dating back to early Māori iwi such as Waitaha and Rapuwai during the early periods of Māori habitation in New Zealand.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Following the arrival of Pākehā in the 19th century, the area saw widespread deforestation, farming, and quarrying, significantly modifying the area's environment.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] As a result of this, the park is one of the most modified landscapes of any of New Zealand's national parks, with management of the park largely focusing on regeneration and restoration of the traditional ecosystem.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The park was first established in 1942 to commemorate the 300th anniversary of Abel Tasman's 1642 visit in New Zealand, when he became the first European to sight the islands.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] It has since been progressively expanded from its original borders, the most recent of which involved the addition of 7 hectares (17 acres) in Awaroa Inlet after a successful crowdfunding campaign.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The coastal area was inhabited for hundreds of years by Māori prior to the arrival of Europeans, with sites throughout the area occupied both seasonally and permanently.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] In addition to harvesting food from the local forests, estuaries and waters, locals grew kūmara.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Historical records indicate a pā was established at Auckland Point by Pohea, who travelled there around 1450 from the Whanganui area.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] From the mid-1500s Muaūpoko (formerly known as Ngāi Tara) occupied the area until the early 1600s, when they were ousted by Ngāti Tūmatakōkiri.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Ngāti Tūmatakōkiri were present when Abel Tasman reached Golden Bay / Mohua in 1642.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The park was founded in 1942, largely through the efforts of ornithologist and author Pérrine Moncrieff to have land reserved for the purpose.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Moncrieff served on the park board from 1943 to 1974.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The park was opened on 18 December 1942 to mark the 300th anniversary of Abel Tasman's visit.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Those in attendance at the opening ceremony at Tarakohe included Charles van der Plas, as personal representative of the Netherlands' Queen, Wilhelmina.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The idea for the park had been under consideration since June 1938.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Crown set aside 15,225 hectares (37,622 acres), comprising 8,900 hectares (21,900 acres) of proposed state forest, 5,809 hectares (14,354 acres) of Crown land and 554 hectares (1,368 acres) of other reserve land for the national park.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Golden Bay Cement Company donated the land where the Abel Tasman Monument and a memorial plaque was sited.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The area's primary historic interest was the visit of Tasman in 1642, D'Urville in 1827, and the New Zealand Company barques *Whitby* and *Will Watch*, and brig *Arrow* in 1841.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The site was also of significant botanical interest.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] By 1946 the park had reached 15,534 hectares (38,386 acres) in area with additional land purchases.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] A further 844 hectares (2,085 acres) at Tōtaranui, formerly owned by William Gibbs, was acquired from J S Campbell in 1949 and added to the park.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] About 6,100 hectares (15,000 acres) have been added since.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] In 2008 an extra 7.9 km2 (790 ha; 3.1 sq mi), including the formerly private land known as Hadfields Clearing, were added to the park.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] In 2016, a further 7 hectares (17 acres) in Awaroa Inlet was purchased by New Zealanders in a crowdfunding campaign.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Covering an area of 237 km2 (92 sq mi; 59,000 acres), the park is the smallest of New Zealand's national parks.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] It consists of forested, hilly country to the north of the valleys of the Tākaka and Riwaka Rivers, and is bounded to the north by the waters of Golden Bay / Mohua and Tasman Bay.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The park contains some of the islands off the coast including the Tata Islands in Golden Bay / Mohua, and Tonga Island, Motuareronui / Adele Island, and Fisherman Island in Tasman Bay.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The park does not extend beyond Mean High Water Mark on the adjacent coast.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Between Mean High Water and Mean Low Water Springs, the beaches are gazetted as a Scenic Reserve, covering 7.74 km2 (2.99 sq mi) in total.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Tonga Island Marine Reserve adjoins part of the park.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Abel Tasman Monument, though not located in the park, commemorates the first contact between Europeans and Māori and is located near the northern end of the park.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Abel Tasman National Park stands out from most other National parks of New Zealand, given that a large area of it has undergone extensive environmental modification in its history.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Early European settlers burned or cleared much of the forest, only to find that the soil was unsuitable for farming.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] This practise not only destroyed much of the shrubland and forests, but also introduced invasive plants found throughout the modern-day park.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] However, as time progresses, the original ecosystems and forests are slowly returning.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The park contains varied habitats, including coastal forests, sub-alpine bogs, and sand dunes.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] As a result of this diversity, many different species can be found.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The islands of the park, in particular Tonga Island, Motuareronui / Adele Island and Fisherman Island which are the largest, have been disturbed less and have no introduced mammalian predators.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] As a result the islands have species not found elsewhere in the park and there are more restrictions to visitor access.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Though much of the parkland is pasture or covered with shrubs, valley areas contain forests of rātā, mataī, miro and hinau.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Over 70 species of birds have been recorded in the park.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Some of the birds that can frequently be seen are petrels, shags, penguins, gulls, terns, and herons.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Possums, wild pigs, deer, and goats can also be seen in the park.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Abel Tasman Coast Track is a popular tramping track that follows the coastline and is one of the Department of Conservation's Great Walks; the Abel Tasman Inland Track is less frequented.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Other walks in the park, such as the Wainui Falls Track are considered "short walks".
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Kayaking, camping and sightseeing are other activities.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Access to the park is usually via the small settlement of Mārahau or Kaiteriteri (by water taxi).
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The nearest large town is Motueka, 20 kilometres (12 mi) to the south.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Dogs (excepting guide dogs) are not allowed in the park.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Department of Conservation administers the National Park.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Scenic Reserve is administered by the Tasman District Council Chief Executive and Department of Conservation's Nelson / Marlborough Conservator.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Activities in adjoining coastal waters are Tasman District Council's responsibility.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] These areas operate under separate regulations.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Interior, consisting of the park areas further inland.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] Park plans include ecological surveys, pest control, and protection of heritage areas and caves.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Islands, encompassing all islands within the park, some of which are closed to the public. key priorities include keeping them free of invasive pests, reintroducing native species, and minimizing human impacts.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] In 2012 Project Janszoon, a privately funded trust, was set up to restore the park's ecosystems.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The trust takes its name from Tasman's middle name *Janszoon*.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] It is aiming to complete the restoration in time for the 400th anniversary of Tasman's visit and the park's 100th anniversary in 2042.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The Department of Conservation and Project Janszoon developed a free virtual visitor centre for downloading to smartphones or tablets.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] The application provides information about the Park's history, its flora and fauna, points of interest, weather, walking tracks, and tides.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/abel-tasman-national-park] This virtual visitor centre is free of charge and can be found through the App Store or Google Play Store.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] It is the largest (by volume) but not tallest species of tree in New Zealand, standing up to 50 metres (160 ft) tall in the emergent layer above the forest's main canopy.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] The tree has smooth bark and small narrow leaves.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Other common names to distinguish *A. australis* from other members of *Agathis* are **southern kauri** and **New Zealand kauri**.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] With its podsolization capability and regeneration pattern it can compete with faster growing angiosperms.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Because it is such a conspicuous species, forest containing kauri is generally known as kauri forest, although kauri need not be the most abundant tree.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] In the warmer northern climate, kauri forests have a higher species richness than those found further south.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Kauri even act as a foundation species that modify the soil under their canopy to create unique plant communities.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Scottish botanist David Don described the species as *Dammara australis*.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] The genus name *Agathis* is derived from Greek and means 'ball of twine', a reference to the shape of the male cones, which are also known by the botanical term strobili.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] The specific epithet *australis* translates in English to 'southern', and was used to distinguish the species from the other members of *Agathis*, which are typically found in more northern tropical areas.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] The Māori name is descended from Proto-Polynesian **kauquli*, a name used to describe various dark-coloured trees in Polynesian languages, including Samoan ebony, or *Diospyros samoensis*.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] The young plant grows straight upwards and has the form of a narrow cone with branches going out along the length of the trunk.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] However, as it gains in height, the lowest branches are shed, preventing vines from climbing.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] By maturity, the top branches form an imposing crown that stands out over all other native trees, dominating the forest canopy.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] The flaking bark of the kauri tree defends it from parasitic plants, and accumulates around the base of the trunk.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] On large trees it may pile up to a height of 2 metres (6 ft 7 in) or more.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Kauri often form small clumps or patches scattered through mixed forests.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Kauri leaves are 3–7 centimetres (1.2–2.8 in) long and 1 centimetre (0.39 in) broad, tough and leathery in texture, with no midrib; they are arranged in opposite pairs or whorls of three on the stem.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] The seed cones are globose, 5–7 centimetres (2.0–2.8 in) diameter, and mature 18 to 20 months after pollination; the seed cones disintegrate at maturity to release winged seeds, which are then dispersed by the wind.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] A single tree produces both male and female seed cones.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Fertilisation of the seeds occurs by pollination, which may be driven by the same or another tree's pollen.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] The largest recorded specimen was known as *The Great Ghost* and grew in the mountains at the head of the Tararu Creek, which drains into the Hauraki Gulf just north of the mouth of the Waihou River (Thames).
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Thames Historian Alastair Isdale says the tree was 8.54 metres (28.0 ft) in diameter, and 26.83 metres (88.0 ft) in girth.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] A kauri tree at Mill Creek, Mercury Bay, known as *Father of the Forests* was measured in the early 1840s as 22 metres (72 ft) in circumference and 24 metres (79 ft) to the first branches.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] It was recorded as being killed by lightning in that period.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Another huge tree, *Kairaru*, had a girth of 20.1 metres (66 ft) and a columnar trunk free of branches for 30.5 metres (100 ft) as measured by a Crown Lands ranger, Henry Wilson, in 1860.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] It was on a spur of Mt Tutamoe about 30 kilometres (19 mi) south of Waipoua Forest near Kaihau.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] It was destroyed in the 1880s or 1890s when a series of huge fires swept the area.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Other trees far larger than living kauri have been noted in other areas.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Rumors of stumps up to 6 metres (20 ft) are sometimes suggested in areas such as the Billygoat Track above the Kauaeranga Valley near Thames.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] However, there is no good evidence for these (e.g., a documented measurement or a photograph with a person for scale).
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Given that over 90 per cent of the area of kauri forest standing before 1000AD was destroyed by about 1900, it is not surprising that recent records are of smaller, but still very large trees.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Two large kauri fell during tropical storms in the 1970s.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] One of these was *Toronui*, in Waipoua Forest.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Its diameter was larger than that of *Tāne Mahuta* and its clean bole larger than that of Te Matua Ngahere, and by forestry measurements was the largest standing.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Another tree, Kopi, in Omahuta Forest near the standing Hokianga kauri, was the third largest with a height of 56.39 metres (185.0 ft) and a diameter of 4.19 metres (13.7 ft).
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Like many ancient kauri both trees were partly hollow.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] In general over the lifetime of the tree the growth rate tends to increase, reach a maximum, then decline.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] A 1987 study measured mean annual diameter increments ranging from 1.5–4.6 millimetres (0.059–0.181 in) per year with an overall average of 2.3 millimetres (0.091 in) per year.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] This is equivalent to 8.7 annual rings per centimetre of core, said to be half the commonly quoted figure for growth rate.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] The same study found only a weak relationship between age and diameter.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] The growth of kauri in planted and second-growth natural forests has been reviewed and compared during the development of growth and yield models for the species.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Kauri in planted forests were found to have up to 12 times the volume productivity than those in natural stands at the same age.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Individuals in the same 10 centimetres (3.9 in) diameter class may vary in age by 300 years, and the largest individual on any particular site is often not the oldest.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Trees can normally live longer than 600 years.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Many individuals probably exceed 1000 years, but there is no conclusive evidence that trees can exceed 2000 years in age.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] By combining tree ring samples from living kauri, wooden buildings, and preserved swamp wood, a dendrochronology has been created which reaches back 4,500 years, the longest tree ring record of past climate change in the southern hemisphere.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] One 1700 year old swamp wood kauri that dates to approximately 42,000 years ago contains fine-scale carbon-14 fluctuations in its rings that may be reflective of the most recent magnetic field flip of the earth.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Much like podocarps, it feeds in the organic litter near the surface of the soil through fine root hairs.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] This layer of the soil is composed of organic matter derived from falling leaves and branches as well as dead trees, and is constantly undergoing decomposition.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] On the other hand, broadleaf trees such as māhoe derive a good fraction of their nutrition in the deeper mineral layer of the soil.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Although its feeding root system is very shallow, it also has several downwardly directed *peg roots* which anchor it firmly in the soil.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Such a solid foundation is necessary to prevent a tree the size of a kauri from blowing over in storms and cyclones.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] The litter left by kauri is much more acidic than most trees, and as it decays similarly acidic compounds are liberated.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] In a process known as leaching, these acidic molecules pass through the soil layers with the help of rainfall, and release other nutrients trapped in clay such as nitrogen and phosphorus.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] This leaves these important nutrients unavailable to other trees, as they are washed down into deeper layers.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] This process is known as podsolization, and changes the soil colour to a dull grey.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] For a single tree, this leaves an area of leached soil beneath known as a cup podsol (de).
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] This leaching process is important for kauri's survival as it competes with other species for space.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Leaf litter and other decaying parts of a kauri decompose much more slowly than those of most other species.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Besides its acidity, the plant also bears substances such as waxes and phenols, most notably tannins, that are harmful to microorganisms.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] This results in a large buildup of litter around the base of a mature tree in which its own roots feed.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] As with most perennials, these feeding roots also house a symbiotic fungi known as mycorrhiza which increase the plant's efficiency in taking up nutrients.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] In this mutualistic relationship, the fungus derives its own nutrition from the roots.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] In its interactions with the soil, kauri is thus able to starve its competitors of much needed nutrients and compete with much younger lineages.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] The fungi on kauri are a food source for the larvae of the New Zealand giraffe weevil, *Lasiorhynchus barbicornis*.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] The larvae of *L. barbicornis* burrow into the wood of a tree for up to two years.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Then *L. barbicornis* exit the bark of the tree as a fully formed adult beetle.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] These adult *L. barbicornis* exit from trees in Spring and Summer and months.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] After emerging from the tree, these adult *L. barbicornis* only live for a few weeks.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] In terms of local topography, kauri is far from randomly dispersed.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] As mentioned above, kauri relies on depriving its competitors of nutrition in order to survive.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] However, one important consideration not discussed thus far is the slope of the land.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Water on hills flows downward by the action of gravity, taking with it the nutrients in the soil.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] This results in a gradient from nutrient poor soil at the top of slopes to nutrient rich soils below.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] As nutrients leached are replaced by aqueous nitrates and phosphates from above, the kauri tree is less able to inhibit the growth of strong competitors such as angiosperms.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] In contrast, the leaching process is only enhanced on higher elevation.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] In Waipoua Forest this is reflected in higher abundances of kauri on ridge crests, and greater concentrations of its main competitors, such as tarairi, at low elevations.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] This pattern is known as niche partitioning, and allows more than one species to occupy the same area.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Those species which live alongside kauri include tawari, a montane broadleaf tree which is normally found in higher altitudes, where nutrient cycling is naturally slow.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Kauri is found growing in its natural ecosystem north of 38°S latitude.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Its conventional southern limit stretches from the Kawhia Harbour in the west to the eastern Kaimai Range.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] However, mature kauri can be found as far south as Christchurch and Dunedin, including in the Dunedin Botanic Gardens.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Its distribution has changed greatly over geological time because of climate change.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] This is shown in the recent Holocene epoch by the migration of kauri southwards after the peak of the last ice age.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] The coldest period in recent times occurred about 15,000 to 20,000 years ago, during which time kauri was apparently confined north of Kaitaia, near the northernmost point of the North Island, North Cape.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Kauri requires a mean temperature of 17 °C (63 °F) or more for most of the year.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] The tree's retreat can be used as a proxy for temperature changes during this period.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] While not present in modern days, the Aupōuri Peninsula in the far north was a refuge for kauri, as large quantities of kauri gum were present in the soils.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] It remains unclear whether kauri recolonised the North Island from a single refuge in the far north or from scattered pockets of isolated stands that managed to survive despite climatic conditions.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] It spread south through Whangārei, past Dargaville and as far south as Waikato, attaining its peak distribution during the years 3000 BP to 2000 BP.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] There is some suggestion that it has receded somewhat since then, which may indicate temperatures have declined slightly.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] During the peak of its movement southwards, it was travelling as fast as 200 metres (660 ft) per year.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Its southward spread is relatively rapid for a tree that can take a millennium to reach complete maturity.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Kauri relies on wind for pollination and seed dispersal, while many other native trees have their seeds carried large distances by frugivores (animals which eat fruit) such as the kererū (native pigeon).
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] However, kauri trees can produce seeds while relatively young, taking only 50 years or so before giving rise to their own offspring.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] This trait makes them somewhat like a pioneer species, despite the fact that their long lifespan is characteristic of K-selected species.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] In good conditions, where access to water and sunlight are above average, diameters in excess of 15 centimetres (5.9 in) and seed production can occur inside 15 years.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Just as the niche of kauri is differentiated through its interactions with the soil, it also has a separate regeneration 'strategy' compared to its broadleaf neighbours.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] This relationship is very similar to the podocarp-broadleaf forests further south.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Kauri demand much more light and require larger gaps to regenerate than such broadleaf trees as pūriri and kohekohe, which show far more shade tolerance.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Unlike kauri, these broadleaf species can regenerate in areas where lower levels of light reach ground level, for example from a single branch falling off.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Kauri trees must therefore remain alive long enough for a large disturbance to occur, allowing them sufficient light to regenerate.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] In areas where large amounts of forest are destroyed, such as by logging, kauri seedlings are able to regenerate much more easily due not only to increased sunlight, but their relatively strong resistance to wind and frosts.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Kauri occupy the emergent layer of the forest, where they are exposed to the effects of the weather; however, the smaller trees that dominate the main canopy are sheltered both by the emergent trees above and by each other.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Left in open areas without protection, these smaller trees are far less capable of regenerating.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] When there is a disturbance severe enough to favour their regeneration, kauri trees regenerate en masse, producing a generation of trees of similar age after each disturbance.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] The distribution of kauri allows researchers to deduce when and where disturbances have occurred, and how large they may have been; the presence of abundant kauri may indicate that an area is prone to disturbance.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Kauri seedlings can still occur in areas with low light but mortality rates increase for such seedlings, and those that survive self-thinning and grow to sapling stage tend to be found in higher light environments.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] During periods with less disturbance, kauri tends to lose ground to broadleaf competitors which can better tolerate shaded environments.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] In the complete absence of disturbance, kauri tends to become rare as it is excluded by its competitors.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Kauri biomass tends to decrease during such times, as more biomass becomes concentrated in angiosperm species like tōwai.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Kauri trees also tend to become more randomly distributed in age, with each tree dying at a different point in time, and regeneration gaps becoming rare and sporadic.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Over thousands of years, these varying regeneration strategies produce a tug of war effect where kauri retreats uphill during periods of calm, then takes over lower areas briefly during mass disturbances.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Although such trends cannot be observed in a human lifetime, research into current patterns of distribution, behaviour of species in experimental conditions, and study of pollen sediments (see palynology) have helped shed light on the life history of kauri.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Kauri seeds may generally be taken from mature cones in late March.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Each scale on a cone contains a single winged seed approximately 5 by 8 millimetres (0.20 in × 0.31 in) and attached to a thin wing perhaps half as large again.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] The cone is fully open and dispersed within only two to three days of starting.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Studies show that kauri develop root grafts through which they share water and nutrients with neighbours of the same species.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Heavy logging, which began around 1820 and continued for a century, has considerably decreased the number of kauri trees.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] It has been estimated that before 1840, the kauri forests of northern New Zealand occupied at least 12,000 square kilometres (4,600 sq mi).
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] The British Royal Navy sent four vessels, HMS *Coromandel* (1821), HMS *Dromedary* (1821), HMS *Buffalo* (1840), and HMS *Tortoise* (1841) to gather kauri-wood spars.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] By 1900, less than 10 per cent of the original kauri survived.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] By the 1950s this area had decreased to about 1,400 square kilometres (540 sq mi) in 47 forests depleted of their best kauri.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] It is estimated that today, there is 4 per cent of uncut forest left in small pockets.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Estimates are that around half of the timber was accidentally or deliberately burnt.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] More than half of the remainder had been exported to Australia, Britain, and other countries, while the balance was used locally to build houses and ships.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Much of the timber was sold for a return sufficient only to cover wages and expenses.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] From 1871 to 1895 the receipts indicate a rate of about 8 shillings (around NZ$20 in 2003) per 100 superficial feet (34 shillings/m3).
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] The Government continued to sell large areas of kauri forests to sawmillers who, under no restrictions, took the most effective and economical steps to secure the timber, resulting in much waste and destruction.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] At a sale in 1908 more than 5,000 standing kauri trees, totalling about 20,000,000 superficial feet (47,000 m3), were sold for less than £2 per tree (£2 in 1908 equates to around NZ$100 in 2003).
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] It is said that in 1890 the royalty on standing timber fell in some cases to as low as twopence (NZ$0.45 in 2003) per 100 superficial feet (8 pence/m3), though the expense of cutting and removing it to the mills was typically great due to the difficult terrain where they were located.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Probably the most controversial kauri logging decision in the last century was that of the National Government to initiate clear fell logging of the Warawara state forest (North of the Hokianga) in the late 1960s.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] This created a national outcry as this forest contains the second largest volume of kauri after the Waipoua forest and was until that time, essentially unlogged (Adams, 1980).
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] The plan also involved considerable cost, requiring a long road to be driven up a steep high plateau into the heart of the protected area.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Logging was stopped in fulfillment of an election pledge by the Labour Government of 1972.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] When the National Party was reelected in 1975, the ban on kauri logging in the Warawara remained in place, but was soon replaced by policies encouraging the logging of giant tōtara and other podocarps in the central North Island.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] The outcry over the Warawara was an important stepping stone towards the legal protection of the small percentage of remaining virgin kauri-podocarp forest in New Zealand's Government-owned forests.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Some Te Tai Tokerau Māori traditions see kauri trees as the legs of Tāne Mahuta, the god of the forest, holding apart the sky and the earth.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Other traditional stories describe kauri and sperm whales as siblings, both children of Tāne Mahuta, one who decided to stay on land, and the other who decided to swim in the oceans.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Kauri wood was traditionally used to create large-scale waka by Māori, which could seat hundreds of people due to the size of the logs.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Although today its use is far more restricted, in the past the size and strength of kauri timber made it a popular wood for construction and ship building, particularly for masts of sailing ships because of its parallel grain and the absence of branches for much of its height.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Kauri crown and stump wood was much appreciated for its beauty, and was sought after for ornamental wood panelling as well as high-end furniture.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Kauri timber was so prevalent in early European settlements that Ferdinand von Hochstetter, when visiting Auckland in 1859, estimated that nearly every building, except those made of stone, had been constructed using kauri timber.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] In the late 19th and early 20th centuries Kauri gum (semi-fossilised kauri resin) was a valuable commodity, particularly for varnish, spurring the development of a gum-digger industry.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Today, the kauri is being considered as a long-term carbon sink.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] This is because estimates of the total carbon content in living above ground biomass and dead biomass of mature kauri forest are the second highest of any forest type recorded anywhere in the world.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] The estimated total carbon capture is up to nearly 1000 tonnes per hectare.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] In this capacity, kauri are bettered only by mature *Eucalyptus regnans* forest, and are far higher than any tropical or boreal forest type yet recorded.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] It is also conjectured that the process of carbon capture does not reach equilibrium, which along with no need of direct maintenance, makes kauri forests a potentially attractive alternative to short rotation forestry options such as *Pinus radiata*.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Kauri is considered a first rate timber.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] The whiter sapwood is generally slightly lighter in weight.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Kauri is not highly resistant to rot and when used in boatbuilding must be protected from the elements with paint, varnish or epoxy to avoid rot.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Its popularity with boatbuilders is due to its very long, clear lengths, its relatively light weight and its beautiful sheen when oiled or varnished.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Its wood holds screws and nails very well and does not readily split, crack, or warp.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Kauri wood darkens with age to a richer golden brown colour.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Very little New Zealand kauri is now sold, and the most commonly available kauri in New Zealand is Fiji kauri, which is very similar in appearance but lighter in weight.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Prehistoric kauri forests have been preserved in waterlogged soils as swamp kauri.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] A considerable number of kauri have been found buried in salt marshes, resulting from ancient natural changes such as volcanic eruptions, sea-level changes and floods.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Such trees have been radiocarbon dated to 50,000 years ago or older.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] The bark and the seed cones of the trees often survive together with the trunk, although when excavated and exposed to the air, these parts undergo rapid deterioration.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] The quality of the disinterred wood varies.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Some is in good shape, comparable to that of newly felled kauri, although often lighter in colour.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] The colour can be improved by the use of natural wood stains to heighten the details of the grain.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] After a drying process, such ancient kauri can be used for furniture, but not for construction.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] The small remaining pockets of kauri forest in New Zealand have survived in areas that were not subjected to burning by Māori and were too inaccessible for European loggers.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] The largest area of mature kauri forest is Waipoua Forest in Northland.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Mature and regenerating kauri can also be found in other national and regional parks such as Puketi and Omahuta Forests in Northland, the Waitākere Ranges near Auckland, and Coromandel Forest Park on the Coromandel Peninsula.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] The importance of Waipoua Forest was that it is the only kauri forest retaining its former virgin condition, and that it was extensive enough to give reasonable promise of permanent survival.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] On 2 July 1952 an area of over 80 square kilometres (31 sq mi) of Waipoua was proclaimed a forest sanctuary after a petition to the Government.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] The zoologist William Roy McGregor was one of the driving forces in this movement, writing an 80-page illustrated pamphlet on the subject, which proved an effective manifesto for conservation.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Waipoua Forest, together with the Warawara to the north, contains three quarters of New Zealand's remaining kauri.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Kauri Grove on the Coromandel Peninsula is another area with a remaining cluster of kauri, and includes the Siamese Kauri, two trees with a conjoined lower trunk.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] In 1921 philanthropic Cornishman James Trounson sold to the Government for £40,000 a large area adjacent to a few acres of Crown land and said to contain at least 4,000 kauri trees.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] From time to time Trounson gifted additional land, until what is known as Trounson Park comprised a total of 4 square kilometres (1.5 sq mi).
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] The most famous specimens are *Tāne Mahuta* and *Te Matua Ngahere* in Waipoua Forest.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] These two trees have become tourist attractions because of their size and accessibility.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Tane Mahuta, named after the Māori forest god, is the biggest existing kauri with a girth of 13.77 metres (45.2 feet), a trunk height of 17.68 metres (58.0 feet), a total height of 51.2 metres (168 feet) and a total volume including the crown of 516.7 cubic metres (18,250 cubic feet).
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Te Matua Ngahere, which means 'Father of the Forest', is smaller but stouter than Tane Mahuta, with a girth (circumference) of 16.41 m (53.8 ft).
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Important note: all the measurements above were taken in 1971.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Kauri is common as a specimen tree in parks and gardens throughout New Zealand, prized for the distinctive look of young trees, its low maintenance once established (although seedlings are frost tender).
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] Kauri dieback was observed in the Waitākere Ranges caused by *Phytophthora cinnamomi* in the 1950s, again on Great Barrier Island in 1972 linked to a different pathogen, *Phytophthora agathidicida* and subsequently spread to kauri forest on the mainland.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/agathis-australis] The disease, known as kauri dieback or kauri collar rot, is believed to be over 300 years old and causes yellowing leaves, thinning canopy, dead branches, lesions that bleed resin, and tree death.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] The mountains, forests, tussock lands and river valleys are used for tramping, fishing kayaking, horse riding and hunting.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] Both the park and neighbouring Ben Avon Station are located near the Aoraki Mackenzie International Dark Sky Reserve, a dark-sky preserve, and are used for astronomy.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] The town is serviced by the tourist town of Omarama.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] The park was established in 2005, and includes the Birchwood Station leasehold farm the New Zealand Government bought back for NZ$10 million in 2004.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] It contained extensive wetlands that had remained largely undeveloped.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] Birchwood Station continued normal farming operations until the end of the leasehold in 2010.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] The road to the former Birchwood Station homestead stopped being regularly maintained by Waitaki District Council in 2011.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] In 2014, ecologist Peter Espie reported a decrease in native plant species in the park, and suggested introducing grazing management.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/ahuriri-conservation-park] Parts of the 2020 Disney film *Mulan* were filmed in the Ahuriri Valley near the conservation park, including the training camp scenes and some battle scenes.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/air-auckland] Flight Hauraki Limited was founded on 17 March 2008 as an associate company of MDR Aviation Ltd, a company specialising in aircraft leases and imports.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/air-auckland] In 2010 Flight Hauraki began operations with a charter and sightseeing service based out of the Salt Air terminal at North Shore Aerodrome.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/air-auckland] These services were operated by a fleet two Cessna 172s and Cessna 207, owned by MDR Aviation Ltd.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/air-auckland] The airline took over management of Air Discovery's Waiheke Island based services to Auckland Airport in March 2012, as well as their sightseeing operation and flights from Great Barrier Island to Auckland.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/air-auckland] Later in 2012, Flight Hauraki took over Salt Air's Kerikeri and Whangārei to North Shore 'Xpress' service, unique in its usage of the Northern Busway to transport passengers to the Auckland city centre relatively traffic free.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/air-auckland] However, this service failed to gain much popularity, so it was cut in February 2013, after less than three months of operation.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/air-auckland] In 2014 the airline moved its main base to Waiheke Island and moved its satellite base to Ardmore.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/air-auckland] From Ardmore the airline began an "Island Hopper" service offering two return daily flights from Ardmore to Waiheke Island and on to Great Barrier Island.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/air-auckland] Flight Hauraki also began many daily unscheduled services to Waiheke Island on demand, aircraft based at each location.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/air-auckland] Founder Paul McSherry sold the company to the New Zealand Aviation Group Limited in 2015, which set a greater focus on tourist operations.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/air-auckland] The airline was renamed in 2018 to Air Auckland.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Akaroa Marine Reserve and the nearby Pōhatu Marine Reserve are no-take zones.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The harbour as a whole has considerable natural values, and the fauna of the inner and outer harbour differs.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] There are pressures on the ecology from human activity, such as settlements on the edge of the harbour, and land and water-based industrial activity.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The marine boundary of Akaroa Marine Reserve is almost entirely surrounded by Akaroa Taiāpure, which occupies the rest of the harbour and the ocean coast between the Akaroa and Pōhatu reserves.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The taiāpure is a local fishing co-management tool for the harbour, which has customarily been of special significance to the hapū as a source of food for spiritual and cultural reasons.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The taiāpure was established over 90 percent of the harbour in February 2006.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] It allows Te Rūnanga o Ngāi Tahu (tribal council) and other fisheries stakeholders to have a say in how the harbour is managed.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Fishing can continue in taiāpure, subject to rules and regulations.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The taiāpure complements the reserve (the remaining 10% of the harbour), as does Pōhatu Marine Reserve just outside the harbour entrance, in Pōhatu / Flea Bay, plus Lyttelton Harbour's Port Levy Mātaitai Reserve and Rāpaki Mātaitai Reserve.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] A *mātaitai* is a permanent reserve created in areas of traditional importance to Māori for customary food gathering.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The two marine reserves are total no-take areas, whereas the taiāpure and mātaitai are fishing enabling and not about the protection of marine life.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Indeed, the *tangata tiaki* (marine guardian) has the power to override fishing regulations, and moreover, the taking of kelp by one pāua farmer is enshrined in the taiāpure legislation.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The Akaroa Taiāpure Management Committee is a non-elected group largely made up of Ngāi Tahu representatives and a range of fisheries interest groups, including recreational, commercial, marine farmers and marine tourism operators.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] This committee has no control over the number of recreational anglers, hence no control over the total number of fish and shellfish taken.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Throughout the 1980s and 1990s, people with local knowledge knew that fish stocks were nowhere near as plentiful as they once were.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Māori who had fished the harbour for decades had lost the opportunity of fishing freely along its shoreline.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The *rūnanga* (committee of senior decision-makers of an *iwi* (tribal group) or *hapū* (family, district groups or community)) knew that pollution and over-fishing had diminished the area of available *mahinga kai* (traditional food gathering areas) within the harbour.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Pollution includes sewage, farm and sub-division run-off as well as algal blooms.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Forest and Bird carried out exploratory dives in Akaroa Harbour in 1990.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The Akaroa Harbour Marine Protection Society formally proposed the establishment of a 560-hectare (1,400-acre) marine reserve in 1996.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The proposal was divisive and led to a two-decade battle that pitted a small group of vocal and determined local residents and divers against recreational anglers, *rūnanga*, commercial fishers and one aquaculturalist.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The local residents wanted a no-take area in the eastern waters of the outer harbour to acts as a breeding pool and as place for dolphins to feed.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Recreational anglers argued "that's where we fish in a northeasterly".
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Te Runanga o Ngāi Tahu claimed strong ties to the area, naming it Te Whata o Kōkiro (meaning the food store-house of Kokiro).
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] When the marine reserve idea was first mooted, commercial fishing was a part of Akaroa's economy and commercial fishers strongly opposed it.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] During the long battle, fish stock declined, and so did commercial fishing.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The original proposal called for a reserve within the harbour.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Fishers counteracted that proposal by applying for and getting a smaller 215 hectares (530 acres) hectares reserve to be located outside of the harbour, at sheltered bay named Pōhatu / Flea Bay.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] While eco-tourism operators were pleased to have something to show to tourists, local iwi continued to express concerns that marine reserves hindered their traditional rights to harvest from the sea.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Meanwhile, the local residents group continued to advocate for a reserve within the harbour.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The Fisheries Act 1996 Part 9 Section 174–175 provides for the establishment of taiāpure/fisheries co-management by local people who care about and have strong ties to an area.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] In January 2004, the Māori Land Court tribunal made a recommendation to the Minister of Fisheries that a taiāpure be granted over the whole of Akaroa Harbour bar one small area subject to the, at that time, proposed Akaroa Marine Reserve.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Judge Wainwright saw no reason why the two could not live together.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] However, this recommendation was successfully appealed by the local pāua farmer and kelp harvester, who claimed a taiāpure would compromise his business.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The High Court sent the case back to the tribunal to gather further evidence about whether the whole of Akaroa Harbour does or does not come within the concept of "littoral coastal waters" of "special cultural significance" to the rūnanga.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The pāua farmer eventually reached an understanding with Ngāi Tahu, ending years of argument.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] He has been granted the rights to harvest giant bladder kelp (*Macrocystis pyrifera*), which he uses to feed the pāua at the Akaroa Paua Farm and also to make garden fertiliser and kelp pepper.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] In contrast, the East Otago Taiāpure explicitly prohibits the harvesting of kelp.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] That ban does not extend to unattached beach-cast kelp.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] There are environmental concerns in Akaroa Harbour regarding the ecological disruption caused by kelp harvesting to wild pāua and other *kaimoana* (sea food).
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The taiāpure was established in February 2006, but the marine reserve took eight more years.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Conservation Minister Kate Wilkinson declined the application for the reserve in 2010 on the grounds that it would adversely affect recreational fishing.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The decision was challenged in the High Court and was quashed in a 2012 ruling.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] In terms of actual numbers, the two separate consultation processes for the application had attracted more support than opposition.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] In April 2013 Conservation Minister Nick Smith announced the approval of the reserve but at the reduced size of 465 hectares (1,150 acres).
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Smith believed the battle had gone on for too long.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The size was reduced to take into account the concerns about customary and recreational fishing.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Subsequently, the size was finalised as 512 hectares (1,270 acres).
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Environment Minister Amy Adams expressed an aspiration for the next step to be integrating the local management of taiāpure and reserve so the two mechanisms work together.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] New Zealand fishing rules place reduced bag limits on many fish species and prohibit shellfish gathering in specific areas.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Tangata tiaki (marine guardians) are appointed for Ōnuku Runanga *rōhe moana* (defined customary fishing area) by the Minister of Primary Industries.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The tangata tiaki (also known as kaitiaki) receive training in bylaws, what quantities of various species can be taken, dates or seasons recommended for harvest, size limits and methods of harvest.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Fishers can get a kaitiaki permit from the tangata tiaki granting permission to take over and above the catch limit, and under the legal size.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] This permit, colloquially called a "chit", is given for *tangihanga* (funeral), *hui* (gathering) and other occasions.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] In addition to upping catch limits, the kaitiaki has the power to override other fishing regulations.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] In 2018, the Department of Conservation trialled a baited underwater video study, which provided a snapshot of the fish communities both within and outside the Akaroa and Pōhatu marine reserves.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] A total of 28 fish species were identified, demonstrating that the baited underwater video technique is an effective method for examining the size and relative abundance of these species.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The study found notable differences in the relative abundances and sizes of blue cod and blue moki in the marine reserves when compared to three taiāpure control areas.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] However, since there is no baseline data for Akaroa Marine Reserve, it would be hasty to link these spatial variations to their protection status.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Nonetheless, the results indicated an increase in the abundance and size of blue cod and moki at Pōhatu reserve compared to earlier studies, and that is likely due to the protection from direct fishing pressure.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] In 2021, a three-year initiative called *Iongairo* was launched to supply data that aids in the management of customary fishing zones and enhances understanding of marine reserves in Te Pātaka o Rākaihautū/Banks Peninsula.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] *Iongairo* focused on identifying and evaluating important habitats—including rock, sand, and mud—and key species such as pāua, mussels, and various types of seaweed.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Additionally, it examined the effects of human activities on the environment.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] Methods included baited underwater cameras, towed and dropped cameras, along with sediment grabs.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akaroa-marine-reserve] The outcome is an interactive online map showcasing the seafloor.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akatarawa-forest] The park is owned and managed by Greater Wellington Regional Council, making it one of the largest landowners in New Zealand.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akatarawa-forest] Akatarawa is a Māori name meaning 'Trailing vines'.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akatarawa-forest] Activities include cycling, hunting, fishing, horse riding, 4WD-vehicle trips and trail biking, including at the Karapoti Gorge.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akatarawa-forest] Akatarawa Forest has ancient northern rātā which predate human habitation of New Zealand, including one tree which is believed to be 1100 years old.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akatarawa-forest] Some of these trees are wider than Tāne Mahuta.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akatarawa-forest] One is largest rātā tree in New Zealand, at 39 metres tall.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akatarawa-forest] Greater Wellington Regional Council carried out a 1080 dropping programme in 2013 to reduce pest species.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akatarawa-forest] A trailbiker was seriously injured in the park in July 2017.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akatarawa-forest] A dirt-biker was rescued from the forest in February 2021.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akatarawa-forest] Between December 2017 and August 2018, a 1.7 kilometre zig-zag track that is part of the Cannon Point Walkway was closed to the public due to a disagreement between Upper Hutt City Council and a private landowner over land access.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akatarawa-forest] In early 2021, Forest and Bird campaigned for Upper Hutt City Council to keep a 35-hectare block as a wildlife corridor and reserve, connecting Akatarawa Forest with Wainuiomata.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/akatarawa-forest] In July 2021, a further 1080 operation was carried out in 2021 to combat a resurgence in possum numbers.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] The area was previously a defensive pā, built by Te Kawerau sub-tribes, occupied until as recently as 1827.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] Ngāti Pāoa ceded the land to the Crown on 5 January 1854, which was subsequently granted to an Austrian, Captain Martin Krippner, in 1860.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] In the 1870s, Major de Grut took over the land until it was sold to the Eaves family in 1919.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] The local Lions began making tracks, building bridges and removing invasive weeds, and the Reserve was formally opened by the Lions Club Chairman, Don Woods on 10 December 1960.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] The daughters of Alice and Edward Eaves were present.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] A series of pedestrian walkways have been constructed through the reserve, as well as a wooden look out point over Orewa Beach that was built in 1997.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] The reserve includes kauri trees as old as 300 years.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] In addition, the bush contains native trees such as tōtara, mataī, kahikatea, pūriri, rata, karaka, rimu, rewarewa, nīkau and taraire.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] A number of these trees can be identified by labels along the walkway.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] Several small streams feed the Nukumea Stream, which marks the reserve's southern boundary.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] The status of the land is Scenic Reserve 19(1)(a) and under the Reserves Act, the management is the responsibility of the Hibiscus and Bays Local Board, elected representatives under the Governing Body, Auckland Council.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] The role of the Board is to make decisions on local matters such as the maintenance and upgrading of facilities, caring for the environment, preservation of heritage and supporting activities in the area.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] In June 2019, the Reserve was required by the Auckland Council to close to the public due to the danger of kauri dieback caused by the spread of a pathogen in contaminated soil possibly being carried on the soles of shoes.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] Lauri Rands from the Eaves Bush Appreciation Society expressed sadness but noted that protection of the 800-year-old kauri in the Reserve was a good example of the importance of taking this action.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] The lower track on the Reserve was re-opened on 30 August 2020 with a hygiene station at the entrance and exit to allow shoes to be cleaned.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] It was noted at the time, that the upper tracks were scheduled for re-opening late in 2021.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] Hibiscus and Bays Local Board Chair Gary Brown expressed delight at the reopening and appreciation to the Council for the work they had done to bring this about.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] He also acknowledged the voluntary contribution of the Eaves Bush Appreciation Group who had worked for years to weed, plant and trap pests.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] Members of this group were the first to walk the re-opened section.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/alice-eaves-scenic-reserve] The Greenways project proposed by the Auckland Council in 2016 had been prioritised by the Hisbiscus and Bays Local Board in 2017 and a feasibility report for implementing walking and cycling connections between the Reserve and Hatfields Beach was completed in 2018.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/aotea-conservation-park] The park includes various habitats including coastal bluffs and freshwater areas.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/aotea-conservation-park] It is home to kauri forest, pōhutukawa (*Metrosideros excelsa*), kānuka (*Kunzea ericoides*), Great Barrier tree daisy (*Olearia allomii*), kākā, brown teal, spotless crake, fernbird, rare frogs, paua slugs and niho taniwha (chevron skink).
[src:aotea-conservation-park/aotea-conservation-park] It is the largest Department of Conservation park in the Auckland Region, similar in size to the Hunua Regional Park and Waitakere Ranges Regional Park.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/aotea-conservation-park] It is also the largest possum-free forest in New Zealand.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/aotea-conservation-park] A major storm in June and July 2014 delayed work to establish the park, and survey the area for Kauri dieback.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/aotea-conservation-park] The park opened the following year in 2015.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/aotea-conservation-park] The Department of Conservation closed some tracks in the park between 2018 and 2020 due to Kauri dieback.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/aotea-conservation-park] The tracks were upgraded, and reopened in January 2020.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/aotea-conservation-park] Auckland Council and Ngāti Rehua Ngati Wai ki Aotea surveyed the park for Kauri dieback in November 2020.
[src:aotea-conservation-park/aotea-conservation-park] In the same month, a report by the Environmental Defence Society concluded the Department of Conservation had a "woeful lack of funding" to manage and protect the park.
